Sunday’s final round of the Magical Kenya Open was broadcast live from the Karen Country Club after the first three days went on without coverage due to logistical challenges. 

Like the Magical Kenya Open won by South Africa’s Justin Harding, the Classic which also forms part of the European Tour series will be a closed event, hence spectators can only the get the action though live TV in some of the designated golf clubs in the country including Karen itself. 

DStv, which has the exclusive pay television rights will air the competiton. In announcing the Channel number and bouquet, MultiChoice Kenya Managing Director, Nancy Matimu said:  

“We are proud that Kenya is hosting two editions of the European Tour for which DStv has the exclusive pay television rights. Our mission is to deliver value to our customers by making great entertainment more accessible. We find and develop the right mix of content and deliver it to Kenyans anytime, anywhere. You can either catch the action from the comfort of your house or anywhere else via DStv Now app," she said. 



